    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter April 18th with a clear hierarchy in offensive expectations, led by **Yordan Alvarez** (77.33) and **Colt Keith** (68.51). **Yordan Alvarez** remains our premier anchor against Pallante, benefiting from a favorable SP_xERA of 4.44 and a significant platoon edge, while **Colt Keith** enjoys an optimized environment against Bello, bolstered by a +13% skill adjustment and a high-leverage spot in the #3 hole. We are also tracking **Pete Crow-Armstrong** (64.51) with intense interest; while his #8 spot is suboptimal, his extreme sprint speed combined with a pitcher whose delivery time favors aggressive base stealing creates a unique ceiling that makes him a mandatory start in our pursuit of the stolen base category.\n\nRisk management defines the rest of our lineup, particularly against high-caliber arms like Chris Sale. Despite facing an elite pitcher, **Trea Turner** (56.27) and **Kyle Schwarber** (54.53) remain high-floor plays due to their leadoff/second-order positioning and elite xwOBA metrics. We are proceeding cautiously with **Caleb Durbin** (42.48); his score is depressed by Tarik Skubal\u2019s 2.71 xERA, and he occupies the bottom of our starting threshold. The most difficult bench decision involved balancing the potential of our depth pieces against these matchups. While **Josh Smith** and **Lars Nootbaar** were considered, they lacked the specific combination of platoon leverage and high-order utility required to displace our current starters. We continue to monitor the status of **Christian Yelich**, **Hyeseong Kim**, **Victor Scott II**, and **Zac Veen**, all of whom remain sidelined, while **Dillon Dingler**, **Jerar Encarnacion**, and **Luis Pena** await their next opportunity to provide bench utility. \n\nFinally, users should note the \"Lineup Pending\" tag for **Kazuma Okamoto** (53.16), whose score is subject to volatility depending on his final placement. Weather risks appear minimal, but the concentration of starts against top-tier arms like Skubal and Sale necessitates strict adherence to our game cap strategy. We are prioritizing speed and OBP potential above all else, ensuring that even in lower-scoring matchups, we maintain the necessary pressure to capture the stolen base category.",
